 account a whole web of mathematical and other practices that are learned and linked by agents, and whose interplay acts as a constraint. Ferreirós demonstrates how advanced mathematics, far from being a priori, is based on hypotheses, in contrast to elementary math, which has strong cognitive and practical roots and therefore enjoys certainty.Offering a wealth of philosophical and historical insights, Mathematical Knowledge and the Interplay of Practices challenges us to rethink some of our most basic assumptions about mathematics, its objectivity, and its relationship to culture and science.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aKnowledge, Theory of. 0aMathematicsxPhilosophy. 7aSCIENCE / Philosophy & Social Aspects.2bisacsh  aAxiom of Choice.  aAxiom of Completeness.  aContinuum Hypothesis.  aElements.  aEuclidean geometry.  aFrameworkЁgent couples.  aGeorg Cantor.  aGreek geometry.  aJ. H. Lambert.  aKenneth Manders.  aPeano Arithmetic.  aPhilip S. Kitcher.  aRiemann Hypothesis.  aSir Isaac Newton.  aZermeloІraenkel axiom system.  aadvanced mathematics.  aagents.  aarbitrary infinity.  aarbitrary set.  aarithmetical knowledge.  aaxioms.  abasic arithmetic.  acertainty.  aclassical arithmetic.  acognition.  acomplementarity.  acomplex numbers.  aconceptual understanding.  acontinuum.  acounting numbers.  acounting practice.  aculture.  adiagrammatic constructions.  adiagrams.  aelementary mathematics.  aexemplars.  aframeworks.  ageometrical proof.  ahistorians.  ahypotheses.  aintuitionistic arithmetic.  alogic.  amathematical activity.  amathematical knowledge.  amathematical objects.  amathematical practice.  amathematics.  ameasuring practices.  ametamathematics.  amethodological platonism.  anatural numbers.  a